    <h2 id="why-dha-prenatal">Why DHA Is the Most Critical Nutrient Missing From Most Prenatal Gummies</h2>

    <p>DHA — docosahexaenoic acid — is an omega-3 fatty acid that constitutes approximately 40% of the polyunsaturated fatty acids in the brain and 60% in the retina. During pregnancy, DHA is transferred from mother to fetus across the placenta, and during the third trimester, the fetal brain accumulates roughly 67mg of DHA per day. This makes DHA arguably the single most important nutrient for fetal neurodevelopment, yet a 2024 analysis of prenatal supplements found that 35% of prenatal gummies on the market contain no DHA whatsoever.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">67mg</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of DHA accumulates in the fetal brain <strong>every single day</strong> during the third trimester. This makes pregnancy one of the highest-demand periods for omega-3 fatty acids in the human lifespan — and why prenatal DHA supplementation is recommended by ACOG, NIH, and the WHO.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends a minimum of 200mg of DHA daily during pregnancy. The National Institutes of Health suggests 300mg. Yet many popular prenatal gummies contain only 50-100mg, or include a generic "omega-3" label that obscures the actual DHA content. This guide identifies the prenatal gummies that deliver meaningful DHA — from verified sources, at documented doses, with third-party testing to confirm what is actually in the bottle.</p>

