        <p>DHA is a structural component of neuronal membranes, influencing synaptic transmission, neurotransmitter release, and myelination. Higher maternal DHA levels correlate with improved infant cognitive scores at 12-18 months.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>DHA for fetal eye development</strong>
        <p>DHA constitutes 60% of the polyunsaturated fatty acids in the retina. Adequate prenatal DHA is associated with better infant visual acuity and reduced risk of early childhood vision problems.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Algal DHA vs. fish oil DHA</strong>
        <p>Algal DHA is sourced from microalgae — the same organisms from which fish obtain their omega-3s. It provides equivalent bioavailability without mercury, PCB, or dioxin contamination risks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Methylfolate over folic acid</strong>
        <p>Approximately 40% of the population carries the MTHFR gene variant that impairs folic acid conversion. Methylfolate (5-MTHF) bypasses this step, ensuring adequate folate regardless of genetics.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2016 meta-analysis in <em>Prostaglandins, Leukotrienes, and Essential Fatty Acids</em> analyzed <strong>10 randomized controlled trials</strong> and found that prenatal DHA supplementation <strong>significantly improved infant visual acuity and cognitive development scores</strong> at 12-18 months. Infants born to mothers with higher DHA levels also had <strong>lower rates of preterm birth</strong> — a finding supported by a 2018 Cochrane review of 70 trials.</p>
      <cite>PLEFA, 2016 — 10 RCTs; Cochrane Review, 2018 — 70 trials</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Why Most Prenatal Gummies Fall Short on DHA</h3>

