    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Prenatal DHA: What the Science Says</h4>
      <p>DHA is the most studied omega-3 fatty acid in the context of pregnancy, with decades of clinical trials supporting its role in fetal neurodevelopment.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>DHA for Brain Development</strong>
          <p>DHA constitutes 40% of polyunsaturated fatty acids in the brain. Fetal accumulation peaks at 67mg/day in the third trimester. Higher maternal levels correlate with improved infant cognition.<br /><em>PLEFA, 2016 — 10 RCTs</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>DHA for Preterm Birth Prevention</strong>
          <p>A 2018 Cochrane review of 70 trials found that omega-3 supplementation during pregnancy reduced the risk of preterm birth by 11% and early preterm birth by 42%.<br /><em>Cochrane Database, 2018</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Methylfolate vs. Folic Acid</strong>
          <p>40% of the population carries the MTHFR variant that impairs folic acid conversion. Methylfolate (5-MTHF) bypasses this step, ensuring adequate folate for neural tube closure.<br /><em>Am J Clinical Nutrition, 2015</em></p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Choline — The Missing Nutrient</strong>
          <p>90% of pregnant women are deficient in choline. It is critical for fetal brain development, neural tube closure, and placental function. Most prenatals omit it entirely.<br /><em>J Am Dietetic Association, 2010</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

