    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Prenatal Gummies With DHA</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why is DHA important during pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>DHA is a critical structural component of the fetal brain and retina. During the third trimester, the fetal brain accumulates approximately 67mg of DHA per day. A 2016 meta-analysis analyzed 10 RCTs and found that prenatal DHA supplementation significantly improved infant visual acuity and cognitive development scores at 12-18 months. ACOG recommends at least 200mg of DHA daily during pregnancy.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much DHA should a prenatal vitamin have?</summary>
      <p>The minimum recommended DHA intake during pregnancy is 200mg per day (ACOG guideline), with many experts recommending 300-350mg. When choosing a prenatal gummy, look for products providing at least 200mg of DHA per serving — not total omega-3s, but specifically DHA.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best source of DHA in prenatal gummies?</summary>
      <p>Algal oil is increasingly preferred because it provides DHA directly from the source (microalgae) without the mercury, PCB, and dioxin concerns associated with fish-derived omega-3s. Algal oil is also suitable for vegetarians and vegans. Fish oil remains effective when purified and third-party tested for contaminants.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I start taking prenatal gummies with DHA?</summary>
      <p>Ideally, start 1-3 months before conception. The neural tube forms within the first 28 days, often before many women know they are pregnant. DHA requirements increase further during the second and third trimesters. Continue through pregnancy and into postpartum, especially if breastfeeding.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take DHA gummies if I have a fish allergy?</summary>
      <p>Yes, if you choose algal-sourced DHA. Algal oil is derived from microalgae, not fish, and is safe for individuals with fish or shellfish allergies. Ritual, Olly, and MegaFood on this list all use algal DHA.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do prenatal gummies with DHA cause fishy burps?</summary>
      <p>Algal DHA gummies virtually eliminate fishy burps because they do not contain fish oil. Fish oil-based gummies may still cause mild fishy burps. To minimize this: store in the refrigerator, take with a meal containing fat, and choose algal-source products.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are prenatal gummies as effective as prenatal pills?</summary>
      <p>Prenatal gummies can be as effective as pills if they contain adequate nutrient doses. The primary advantage of gummies is compliance — a 2019 survey found that 74% of adults who switched from pills to gummies reported higher adherence. However, gummies typically cannot include iron. For pregnant women who struggle with pill swallowing or morning sickness, a DHA-containing prenatal gummy is better than skipping supplementation entirely.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take additional DHA if my prenatal only has 100mg?</summary>
      <p>Yes. If your prenatal provides less than 200mg DHA, add a standalone DHA supplement or consume 2-3 servings of low-mercury fish per week. The FDA recommends 8-12 ounces of low-mercury fish per week during pregnancy. The key is reaching a minimum of 200mg DHA daily from all sources combined.</p>
    </details>

